<HEADLINE>
<P>
ELECTION PANEL OKS GORE'S BANK LOANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. (D-Tenn.) did not receive favored treatment from banks 
that lent him $1.6 million for his unsuccessful campaign for the Democratic 
presidential nomination, the Federal Election Commission reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Most of the loans were taken out around March, 1988, when a large number of 
primaries were held in the South. The Tennessee senator had pinned much of his 
hopes for winning the nomination on those primaries. 
</P>
<P>
Election commission auditors initially questioned whether some of the banks had 
received enough collateral and assurances of repayment. Gore's campaign argued 
that the loans had been repaid in full, which should serve as proof of the 
soundness of the decision to lend the money. 
</P>
