<P>
Some FM Stations Can Boost Signals: The Federal Communications Commission has 
approved new rules that will allow thousands of FM stations serving small 
communities to double their signal strengths and reach larger audiences. The 
commission, in a 3-0 vote, said so-called Class A FM stations could boost their 
power from the present limit of 3,000 watts up to 6,000 watts. The commission 
also revised the distances by which Class A stations must be separated from 
other stations to limit interference. Existing stations that do not meet the 
revised separation requirements will be "grandfathered," and will be allowed to 
move their antennas or request permission to use directional antennas. 
</P>
