<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MUSIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Maria Casale, 26, of North Hollywood is one of four finalists in the the U.S.A. 
International Harp Competition that will wrap up this evening in Bloomington, 
Ind. Two other Americans and and a 19-year-old girl from France are the other 
finalists. All four will perform solo and with orchestra tonight before a 
winner is selected. The harp competition is the first in the United States in 
20 years. It was founded by Susann McDonald, professor of music at Indiana 
University and chair of the school's harp department. Thirty-seven harpists 
from 14 countries have performed at the IU School of Music since the 
competition began July 4. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
