<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
SLUMAN CLUBS HOT AT BELGIAN CLASSIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BRUSSELS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American Jeff Sluman today almost equaled the record of the Royal Golf Club of 
Belgium on the opening day of the $1-million Belgian Classic. Sluman had a 
7-under-par 66, one shot off the 54-year-old record of 65 set by Belgian Flory 
Van Donck, to take the first-round lead. Nick Price shot the last 66 at the 
Royal Golf Club, and that was 10 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
American Larry Mize, with a 4-under-par 69, finished three shots behind Sluman. 
</P>
<P>
The favorite, Australian Greg Norman, tied for third with American Chip Beck, 
Scott Simpson and Andy Bean at 72. 
</P>
<P>
American Tom Kite was seventh at 74 and Jack Nicklaus Jr. was eighth after 
firing a 3-over 76. Nicklaus had a 5-under-par 68 in a pro-am round on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
The Belgian Classic ends on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
